passages.text: Weekly Fast Track: Tariffs May Splinter Furniture Imports, CPKC Service Improvements, De Minimis Drop?

This weekly publication highlights current transports and logistics trends across a wide range of truckload, intermodal, LTL, ocean, and airfreight market metrics. The rail section also includes a report card that simplifies how the network is performing relative to history and peers while also tracking carload trends versus consensus expectations.

Key topic of the week: Potential furniture import tariffs and import update. Last Friday, President Trump threatened to impose tariffs on furniture imports to the U.S. following an investigation to determine the appropriate level that should be completed within 50 days. The details of the proposed policy remain unknown, but we expect a negative impact on furniture import demand as a portion of the tariffs are passed through to consumers. Furniture has historically commanded a significant share of total U.S. imports, with a 12- year range between 11- 17%. Currently, furniture represents \(\sim 12\%\) of total U.S. imports, and in absolute terms the number of TEUs is still toward the upper end of the 12- year range (see Figures 5 & 6). From our Descartes import volume database, we estimate \(\sim 55\%\) of furniture imports come from China, which is down from \(\sim 65\%\) in 2013- 2018 (Figure 8). As shown in Figure 7, we think there has been a pull- forward in furniture imports ahead of tariffs, with \(+3,100\) bps of outperformance from November 2024 - March 2025 and \(- 4,700\) bps of underperformance from April 2025 - July 2025. We believe Truckload and Intermodal are the most exposed surface transportation sub- sectors to furniture imports and therefore stand to lose the most from any tariff impact. Looking at the broader mosaic of all imports, our most recent look at the high frequency import and booking data showed another strong week of inbound containers to the SoCal ports after last week we saw a surprising uptick following a record month for July (Figure 9). This recent strength still seems like an outlier in the context of our other data sets, specifically containership bookings from China to the U.S. are now down \(- 26\%\) YoY (underperforming seasonality by \(- 3,250\) over the past 7 weeks) and all bookings to the U.S. are now down \(- 15\%\) YoY (underperforming seasonality by \(- 2,030\) bps over the past 7 weeks) - see Figures 13- 16. This week (Week 34), U.S. containerized imports rose \(+7\%\) WoW, outperforming seasonality by \(+700\) bps to \(+2\%\) YoY (see Figure 11 & 12). We believe the past week's import boost reflects the stronger containership data, but we expect sub- seasonal trends through year- end as 2H25 starts to look directionally similar to the post- Covid normalization in 2H22, which implies double- digit import volume declines in 1H26 on a YoY.

Truck: Spot rates ex- fuel fell \(- 0.7\%\) WoW for dry van and bumped up \(+1.1\%\) and \(+0.6\%\) WoW for reefers and flatbed, as dry van underperformed seasonality while reefers and flatbed outperformed. We note that these rates are through 8/24 and do not yet reflect the impact of the CVSA's Brake Safety Week, which began on 8/24 and will end on 8/30 (more details here). Dry van spot rates are now \(+1\%\) YoY, \(+3\%\) vs 2019 levels and have cumulatively outperformed seasonality by \(+355\) bps YTD

Dry van tender rejection rates increased \(+60\) bps WoW, which was a \(+55\) bp outperformance of normal Week 34 seasonality, bringing the YTD outperformance to \(+575\) bps. Dry van freight volume tendered bumped up \(+3\%\) WoW but is still down \(- 15\%\) YoY. The dry van load-to-truck ratio fell \(- 2\%\) WoW, as load posts were up \(+4\%\) and truck posts increased \(+6\%\) . The weekly count of net changes of motor carrier authorizations flipped back positive with \(+52\) net authorities added. The 2025 YTD average is now - 29 net revocations per week compared to the 2024 average of - 246 weekly net revocations.

Rail: Last week, CPKC provided another update on the progress of its Service Action Plan requested by STB Chairman Fuchs following the congestion issues caused by the May 3 consolidation of CPKC's U.S. IT systems. CPKC initially targeted a return to normal service level in the second half of July, and the company appears to be on track with that objective based on the most recent update. Specifically, for the month of July, CPKC's first- mile/ last- mile performance was well above the service action plan trigger point and their manifest on- time performance is now \(60\%\) , which is above the service action plan trigger point but below the pre- integration levels of \(75\%\) . CPKC had been operating in the "Fair" category (one notch below Average) for the past 12 weeks, but returned to the "Average" category this week (See Figure 2). We believe the CPKC network has regained positive operating momentum, with system dwell and cars online down \(- 7\%\) and \(- 2.5\%\) , while car velocity is up \(+3\%\) compared to the worst point of the disruption in early 2Q25.

For each of the three categories, the score is based on the quintile it fits into based on the historical data for that week. As an example, for system dwell we give points if the week's dwell is in the bottom \(20\%\) of historical data for this week for this railroad, 1 point if in the next lowest \(20\%\) and then score. The sum is then between - 6 (worst possible score) and 6 (best possible score) where we then classify the overall status as Poor, Fair, Average, Good, or Excellent.

**Airfreight:** Rates on the China to U.S. lane for Week 3 ending Aug 24 ticked down -2%WoW, standing at -13% YoY and underperforming seasonality by -350bps, bringing the cumulative YTD seasonal performance up, 400bps. U.S. Europe was the best performing major lane last week with a +9% WoW increase in rates while the Europe to U.S. lane fell the most at -6% WoW. China to U.S. is the 5th weakest of the six major lanes tracked in Figures 178-183 based on YTD seasonality, with U.S. to Europe remaining the strongest and Europe to U.S. the weakest. Volume data is available on a one-week lag to rates, and tonnage from APAC to the U.S. dropped -9% WoW with nearly half of the fall attributed to Japan's -53% WoW decline due to temporary business closures resulting from Japan's three-day Obon festival. WoW declines from China (-6%), HK (-3%), Thailand (-12%) and Singapore (-19%) also contributed meaningfully to the fall. Removal of de minimis by U.S. for all origins from Aug 29 onwards has led to the suspension of mail shipments to the U.S. from global postal carriers until further notice as they face tight deadlines to comply with the unexpected change, which we anticipate could be reflected in volume and rate data in the coming weeks.
Figure 3: WoW changes in weekly airfreight rates across 10 major lanes
Source: TAC, J.P. Morgan estimates, Note: Data in local currency.

**Ocean:** Far East to USWC rates for Week 34 ending Aug 24 decreased by -3% WoW,underperforming seasonality by -700bps, standing at -73% YoY, indicating a cumulative seasonal underperformance of -12,200bps YTD. Far East to South America East Coast was the worst performing lane this week with a -12% WoW decrease, with USWC to Far East lane performing the best with a +2% WoW increase. Far East to USWC is the weakest of the six major lanes tracked in Figures 171-176 based on YTD seasonality, with USEC to North Europe remaining the strongest at +300bps. Far East to USWC rates are now down -65% from its recent peak reached in Week 23 and -68% down from Week 1, which was the highest recorded value for the current year.

STB Service Metrics - On-time arrival percentage is calculated as the number of manifest carloads that arrive at their final destination within 24 hours of the original estimated time of arrival, divided by the total number of manifest carloads. Successful local service percentage measures the number of cars placed at their final destination within 24 hours of the commitment, divided by the total number of cars with local service commitments.
